FINS Seafood & Dive Bar, Cape Coral: JLB restaurant review News Cape Coral Sports Opinion Restaurants Advertise Obituaries eNewspaper Legals JEAN LE BOEUF FINS Seafood & Dive Bar, Cape Coral: JLB review At FINS Seafood & Dive Bar in Cape Coral, a massively meaty crab cake helps make up for this all-over-the-place menu. JEAN LE BOEUF JLEBOEUF@NEWS-PRESS.COM The crab cake came at just the right time. It was, let’s just say, a slow start for my party at the 2-months-old FINS Seafood & Dive Bar in Cape Coral. The appetizers — a dry take on ahi-tuna nachos, and a lackluster, slightly mushy bowl of peel-and-eat shrimp — had sent our table into an awkward silence. A slurp of sangria here. An adjusting of plates there. Looking for a free mini puzzle? Play the USA TODAY Quick Cross now. A clear-your-throat cough to fill the dead air. I hate to say I’d written the place off after just those two dishes. But I wasn’t optimistic. And then the clouds parted and the angels sang and — crab cake. I didn’t even recognize it as a crab cake at first, more as a mound of jumbo-lump crab held together by the faintest hint of — is that remoulade? — and some inexplicable magic. It was just one “cake,” but it was at least ⅓-pound of crab, the meaty kind plucked carefully from under the shell. I ogled it, photographed it (as good 21st century food critics do), then dove in thinking I may never resurface. It’s dishes such as this one that make me wonder about FINS. The restaurant opened in early February in the former Carmine Street NY Pizza & Mussels building on Del Prado Boulevard a few blocks south of Cornwallis Parkway. The formerly dark and low-ceilinged space has been brightened and opened and thoroughly beach-ified, in a kitschy (there’s a scuba diving mannequin), tiki-hut (there’s one of those, too) sort of way. Cape eats: On Del Prado, a dining renaissance The chef is formerly of Ford’s Garage. The owners are from Maryland — hence said crab cake, and, another day, my thick burger charred to medium perfection on a lightly toasted brioche bun (I thought it tasted familiar). But, as we’ve learned here, such perfection can be fleeting. For every great burger I had there was a sad flatbread, its crust doughy and not-quite crisp.  Or a beige plate of seafood enchiladas that looked like some kind of Red Lobster-Taco Bell mashup (but that tasted far better than it looked, to be fair). Many of FINS’ dishes just don’t make sense: the cheesesteak, the turkey Reuben, the Bucket (yes, Bucket) of Ribs. Your hope fades again, but is renewed by a bracing ceviche brimming with seafood in a limey, pale yellow marinade. And by a crisp side of pineapple-flecked slaw that flickers with jalapenos, and an old-school smoked fish dip that’s served in that velvety, easy-to-spread style I love. JLB Picks: 5 SWFL places serious about seafood FINS knows its way around a cocktail, as well. The bar, which can get a little too umbrella-froufrou for me at times, crafts a mean Bloody Mary, and an even meaner Matlacha Mule made with grapefruit vodka, ginger beer and mango puree. The waitress guided my friend to a refreshing pineapple cider one lunch, then to a citrusy IPA from the lengthy list of craft drafts. I found FINS’ service to be far more even than its food; knowledgeable and quick, friendly but not smothering. And while not every plate was a knockout, the seafood basket toppling with fried grouper, shrimp, oysters, and crisp, hand-cut fries (a flat out bargain at $16.95) gave that crab cake a run for its cloud-parting money. As did the flaky, forearm-length fillet of Atlantic cod in the fish and chips. On my most recent visit to FINS, the server mentioned they were making changes to the menu, “streamlining,” I think was the word she used. She also said the crab cakes, currently only available at dinner, would soon be offered all day long. Music to my ears.
